Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code for your `BackgroundProcessor`.

## Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Exception as control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent to the old ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control the loop.
                // Loop will exit naturally via the while condition.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread did not exit within 2s.
            // In modern .NET there is NO way to forcibly kill it.
            // Log a warning — see pitfalls below.
            Console.Error.WriteLine("Worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }

        _cts.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key Changes & Pitfalls

**1. `GetNextItem()` must accept the token.** This is the most critical point. If it blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection` or socket), cancellation won't fire until it unblocks. Fix:

```csharp
// Before (blocks forever, ignores cancellation):
var item = queue.Take();

// After (wakes up when cancelled):
var item = queue.Take(token);          // BlockingCollection<T>
// or
var item = await channel.ReadAsync(token); // System.Threading.Channels
```

**2. No force-kill equivalent exists.** `Thread.Abort()` has **no replacement** in .NET 8 — the runtime will throw `PlatformNotSupportedException`. If `GetNextItem` calls uncooperative code you can't modify, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`.

**3. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone.** The old pattern caught `ThreadAbortException`, called `ResetAbort()`, and let the loop continue. With cooperative cancellation, you simply check `token.IsCancellationRequested` in the `while` condition — no reset needed. If you want to continue processing after a per-item cancellation, use a **per-item `CancellationTokenSource`** linked to a parent:

```csharp
using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // per-item timeout
```

**4. `Thread.Sleep` in `Stop()` replaced with `Join(timeout)`.** The original `Sleep(2000)` was a race condition — `Join` properly waits for thread exit.

**5. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It's `IDisposable` and leaks timers/callbacks if not disposed.

**6. Cancellation is not instant.** Unlike `Thread.Abort()` which injected an exception at any point, `OperationCanceledException` only fires at explicit checkpoints (`token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`, or APIs that accept the token). Add checkpoints inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running:

```csharp
private void ProcessItem(object item, CancellationToken token)
{
    Step1(item);
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
    Step2(item);
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
    Step3(item);
}
```
